<?php	$description = 'Start your troubleshooting on this page: A list of the known issues for the caroufredsel plugin.';	$keywords = 'known, issues, problems, help, troubleshooting, carousel';	$title = 'Known issues - Support';	include_once '../functies/layout_pre.php';?>				<div id="usage">					<h1>Known issues</h1>					<br />					<h4 id="_wrongsize">The carousel has a wrong width and/or height.</h4>					<p>To ensure the plugin is able to measure the correct sizes, always use <code>display: block;</code> for the items.<br />						In a horizontal carousel, you should also make the items <code>float: left;</code>.</p>					<div class="script"><pre class="brush: css;">#foo img {	display: block;	float: left;}</pre>					</div>					<br />					<p>If you're scrolling images, don't forget to specify a width and height. Otherwise the plugin might not be able to measure the correct size of the images onDocumentReady (mostly on Webkit browsers Chrome and Safari).</p>					<div class="script">						<p class="head"><strong>Using the HTML attributes:</strong></p><pre class="brush: xml;">&lt;img src=&quot;image1.jpg&quot; width=&quot;140&quot; height=&quot;140&quot; /&gt;</pre>					</div>					<br />					<div class="script">						<p class="head"><strong>Via CSS:</strong></p><pre class="brush: css;">#foo img {	width	: 140px;	height	: 140px;}</pre>					</div>					<br />					<div class="script">						<p class="head"><strong>Via the plugin configuration:</strong></p><pre class="brush: jscript;">$(&quot;#foo&quot;).carouFredSel({	items	: {		width	: 140,		height	: 140	}});</pre>					</div>					<br />					<br />					<h4 id="_iecomma">The carousel does nothing in IE</h4>					<p>If the plugin seems to do nothing at all in Internet Explorer, chances are you have a <a href="http://www.google.nl/search?q=trailing+comma+ie" target="_blank">trailing comma</a> where it does not belong.</p>					<br />					<h4 id="_iefade">&quot;Fade&quot; and &quot;crossfade&quot; in IE</h4>					<p>The effects &quot;fade&quot; and &quot;crossfade&quot; don't fade all kinds of HTML-elements in some versions of Internet Explorer.<br />						This is probably due to the fact that IE has problems fading elements with <code>position: relative;</code>, try not to use it in combination with one of the fading effects.</p>				</div> <!-- /usage --><?php	include_once '../functies/layout_post.php';?>